#import "template.typ": *

#let metadata = (
  title: "Short and Soft Field Operations",
  unit: "Group A (3-Axis) | Phase 2 — Stage C6 | E8, E11, E12",
  author: "C.Moroney",
)

#let lesson = (
title: [Short and Soft Field Operations]

,aim: [
Conduct short field and soft field takeoffs and landings to C standard using correct technique and performance calculations.
]

,overview: [
Stage C6 is a dedicated dual lesson covering short field and soft field operations. It is always conducted as a separate lesson, regardless of whether elements were touched on during C5 dual checks. Solo short and soft field operations are not required before the flight test — C standard must be demonstrated before the flight test, but this can be achieved in dual training. The student is fully independent in all pre-flight administration by this stage.
]

,learning_outcomes: [
#text(size:12pt)[*Knowledge*]
- Calculate takeoff and landing performance using the POH
- Explain the effect of runway surface on takeoff and landing distance (sealed vs grass vs soft)
- Describe emergency braking technique: maximum pedal pressure; rearward elevator; avoid lockup on unsealed surfaces
- Explain the effect of runway slope on performance
- Describe the safety margins applied to calculated performance figures

#text(size:12pt)[*Skills*]
- Calculate takeoff and landing performance from POH data with appropriate safety margins
- Conduct a short field takeoff to C standard
- Conduct a short field landing to C standard
- Conduct a soft field takeoff to C standard
- Conduct a soft field landing to C standard

#text(size:12pt)[*Non-Technical Skills*]
- [SA] Assess runway condition before flight; confirm surface is suitable for the intended operation
- [TEM] Performance calculations are a threat management tool — use conservative assumptions; apply safety margins; abort if margins are not met
- [CRM] Brief calculated performance figures and technique selection to instructor before each takeoff
]

,theory_knowledge: [
- Aeroplane Performance — density altitude, short/soft field performance, takeoff distances *(Pg 145, 241, 245)*
- Air Legislation — pilot responsibility for performance assessment *(Pg 88)*
]

,ground_brief_topics: [
Total time: 35 minutes \
Equipment required: POH, performance charts, whiteboard \

*Non-Technical Skills* (5 minutes)
- [TEM] Performance calculations prevent accidents — always use conservative inputs; apply 1.5 × calculated distance as minimum operating margin; if the margin is not met, do not attempt the operation
- [SA] Runway assessment before flight: surface condition, slope, obstacles, surface wind; if uncertain about the surface — do not operate
- [CRM] Brief performance figures before departure

*Performance Calculation* (10 minutes)
- Using POH charts: temperature, density altitude, wind component, and aircraft weight as inputs
- Density altitude: understand its effect on both takeoff and landing distance
- Safety margin: minimum 1.5 × calculated distance as operating margin for training operations
- Takeoff distance available (TODA) vs required: confirm margin before every departure; account for surface condition factor
- Landing distance available (LDA) vs required: confirm margin; account for surface condition factor

*Short Field Technique* (5 minutes)
- Takeoff: brakes held; full power set and checked; release; controls neutral; rotate at Vr without delay; climb at Vx to clear obstacle; transition to Vy when obstacle cleared
- Landing: approach with full flaps in a level attitude; stable gate met at 300 ft; aim for just before threshold (up to 50 m) if safe; firm touchdown just past threshold; maximum effective braking; full rearward elevator during rollout
- Key discipline: fly the attitude precisely — extra airspeed directly adds to landing distance

*Soft Field Technique* (5 minutes)
- Takeoff: continuous rolling start — never stop on soft surface; lift off at minimum speed; immediately lower nose to accelerate in ground effect; climb away after airspeed builds
- Landing: normal approach; smooth hold-off; hold nose up throughout rollout to transfer weight progressively; avoid hard braking on soft surface; taxi clear immediately without stopping

*Emergency braking* (5 minutes)
- Maximum braking: pressure applied smoothly until wheel lockup is felt, release slightly
- On grass or soft surfaces: do not lock the wheels
- Use full rearward elevator during rollout to transfer weight rearward, reducing nosewheel load and improving braking traction on the main wheels
- When to use: overrun risk; rejected takeoff; unexpected obstacle after touchdown; forced landing
- Brake temperature: emergency braking raises temperature rapidly; repeated emergency braking can damage the brakes or cause a fire (especially with wheel covers)
- In an emergency: consider ground looping if overrun imminent and go-around not possible
]

,ground_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Instructor*]
- Spot-check student's performance calculation and safety margin application
- Review maintenance release with student; sign the release
- Confirm runway surface and conditions are suitable for short/soft field operations

#text(size:12pt)[*Student*]
- Complete performance calculation using POH; apply safety margins; brief calculated figures to instructor
- Access NAIPS independently; obtain TAF/GAF/GPWT; brief to instructor
- Check NOTAMs independently; brief to instructor
- Review maintenance release independently; brief instructor on content and anything noted before instructor signs
- Complete IMSAFE self-assessment and operations whiteboard
- Deliver pre-takeoff safety brief before taxi; include calculated performance figures and technique selection
]

,in_flight_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Demonstration*]
- Instructor demonstrates one short field takeoff and one short field landing; patter timing, technique, and discipline on attitude and airspeed
- Instructor demonstrates one soft field takeoff; patter continuous roll, ground effect acceleration, and rollout technique

#text(size:12pt)[*Student Practice*]
- Short field takeoff: minimum 3 repetitions; instructor assesses timing of rotation and Vx control
- Short field landing: minimum 3 repetitions; go-around on any that are not on target or that miss the stable approach gate
- Soft field takeoff: minimum 2 repetitions
- Soft field landing: minimum 2 repetitions
- Note: solo short/soft field operations are not required before the flight test
]

,common_errors:[
- *Short field: rotating late*: Rotate at Vr precisely — delay adds distance.
- *Short field landing: carrying extra airspeed*: Fly the attitude; positive touchdown.
- *Short field landing: hold-off too high*: Reduced hold-off compared to normal; land precisely; do not float.
- *Performance calc: no safety margin*: Calculated figures assume ideal conditions; apply 1.5 × without exception.
]

,post_flight:[
- *Student Self-Assessment* (5 min): Review each takeoff and landing; compare technique to what was briefed; note attitude and airspeed discipline.
- *Instructor Feedback* (10 min): Compare actual technique to calculated figures; identify specific technique elements to refine toward C standard.
- *Performance calc debrief*: Were inputs correct? Were margins applied? Did actual performance reflect the calculated figures?
]

,standards_for_progression:[
*Note: Solo short/soft field operations are not required before the flight test. C standard must be demonstrated in dual training before the flight test.*

#text(size:12pt)[*Progressing (P)*]
- *Short field takeoff*: Rotation at Vr with minor delay; Vx maintained −0/+5 kts; technique improving
- *Short field landing*: Gate met; threshold speed −0/+5 kts; touchdown within ±50 m of target; braking applied
- *Soft field takeoff*: Continuous roll attempted; lifts off near minimum speed; some delay in lowering nose for ground effect acceleration
- *Soft field landing*: Smooth hold-off; nose held up with minor prompt; no heavy braking

#text(size:12pt)[*Certificate Standard (C) — required before flight test*]
- *Short field takeoff*: Brakes held; full power checked; rotation at Vr precisely; Vx ±3 kts to obstacle; performance within calculated figures
- *Short field landing*: Gate met at 300 ft; threshold crossing speed ±3 kts; touchdown at or within ±20 m of target; effective maximum braking; minimum rollout
- *Soft field takeoff*: Continuous roll; lift-off at minimum speed; acceleration in ground effect before climb; no hesitation or technique errors
- *Soft field landing*: Smooth hold-off; nose held up throughout rollout; no hard braking; aircraft clear of soft surface promptly
- *Performance calculation*: Correct inputs; appropriate safety margins applied; figures briefed clearly before departure

- *Outcome*: Recorded in training record as P or C with specific comments per technique type. C standard required before flight test.
]

,safety:[
- *Weather*: Standard dual minima apply; visibility >5 km; wind within limits
- *Runway surface*: Confirm surface condition before conducting soft or short field operations
- *Performance margin*: Confirm adequate runway margin before every short field operation; if margin is not met — do not attempt
- *TEM*:
  - Short field operations have reduced margins for error — heightened alert monitoring throughout approach and landing
  - Be prepared to take control if directional control is lost on rollout
]

,homework:[
- Read Bob Tait's RAAus Study Guide:
  - Aeroplane Performance: Pg 145, 241, 245 (density altitude, performance charts, short field data)
  - Air Legislation: Pg 88 (pilot responsibility for performance assessment)
- Reflect:
  - "How would a hot, humid summer day at a grass strip change your takeoff performance calculation? What additional margins would you apply?"
  - "What would you do if you were committed to a short field landing and found yourself high on final at 400 ft?"
]
)

